WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.639
So, hello, I'm Jeff Arnold, formerly of Insight Data Science as a data science fellow, and

00:00:17.639 --> 00:00:23.280
will be working at Instacart beginning of January as a data scientist, so I should get

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:27.920
used to saying things like, my opinions do not necessarily represent the opinions of

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:32.119
anyone who has or ever will employ me.

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:37.439
Probably don't represent the opinions of myself in the past or the future.

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:44.560
So this is a bit of a click-baity title, I realize, after the fact.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:51.720
If you're parsing it as Solving R for data science, I'm not going to do that.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:56.520
Most of the people here are doing that far better than I, so I will give you time to

00:00:56.520 --> 00:01:01.360
leave if you're expecting me to solve R for all of data science.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:10.919
Instead, I'm solving R for data science, as in R for data science, which needs no introduction,

00:01:10.919 --> 00:01:19.680
by Wickham and Grohlman, and I made exercise solutions to it, and that's what I'm going

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:22.279
to be discussing.

00:01:22.279 --> 00:01:27.320
So hopefully that's not too much of a letdown.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:34.760
So as one would expect, these are a set of exercise solutions to all exercises in R for

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:35.760
data science.

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:47.120
It is up on GitHub, as one is wont to do, and it is all done with Bookdown and compiled

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:49.639
to a nice, pretty website.

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:52.800
Why did I write these solutions?

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:55.800
What was I thinking at the time?

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.760
And I had to go back to reflect upon it.

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:02.839
But the main thing was, this was from my previous life as an academic.

00:02:02.839 --> 00:02:06.599
So I was using R for data science in a course.

00:02:06.599 --> 00:02:12.119
I was responsible for teaching the first-year sequence of quantitative methods to social

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:17.119
science PhD students, at least with the students I had.

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:22.199
I really couldn't assume any sort of prior statistical experience, nor any prior programming

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:28.800
experience, and they were interested in getting to do applied research, not in the theory

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:33.839
behind it, necessarily, except to the extent that it moves that forward, which is actually

00:02:33.839 --> 00:02:38.960
kind of perfect, because I really like this book in the sense that it's not a book about

00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:43.919
R as a programming language per se, nor is it a book about statistics that happens to

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:46.199
use R on the side.

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:54.479
It really starts with getting people into using R to get their job done.

00:02:54.479 --> 00:02:59.160
And at least when I took quantitative methods courses, it was a lot of this.

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:06.639
I know a lot of people here are improving that curricula, and so I don't expect this

00:03:06.639 --> 00:03:09.080
to be the case much longer.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:18.039
But in practice, most applied research is a lot more like this.

00:03:18.039 --> 00:03:23.720
There's the importing, the tidying, the transforming, the visualizing, the modeling, and of that

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:30.559
modeling, the proofs behind why all that statistical inference works is a very small sliver of

00:03:30.559 --> 00:03:36.399
it, a very important sliver, one that we cannot ignore, but you have to go through a lot of

00:03:36.399 --> 00:03:38.800
stuff just to get there.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:43.080
And that's why I adopted this textbook, and it was great.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:49.320
Now I could spend more time working with the students and less time writing more and more

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:52.039
of the same material.

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:57.679
But it was a new book, so I was like, well, I should probably see what's in it if I'm

00:03:57.679 --> 00:03:59.320
going to assign it.

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:02.759
And so I just kind of sat down and worked through it.

00:04:02.759 --> 00:04:07.960
I knew Tidyverse, so it was fun.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:14.880
And then, you know, put it up on GitHub, and I didn't want to make it too obvious that

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:23.079
it was R for data science, and so, you know, I took the ROT13 of it and called it E4QF.

00:04:23.079 --> 00:04:31.320
I'm clearly not too good with the cryptography, so there's these things called search, and

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:34.320
apparently people found it.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:39.679
And so, yeah, so that's really how I got there.

00:04:39.679 --> 00:04:44.519
And so all of this happened about, like, the month before, actually, I think, R for data

00:04:44.519 --> 00:04:46.000
science was even published.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.040
I think I assigned it prior to the official publication date.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:57.799
Did that, put it up there, you know, told my students they could look at it.

00:04:57.799 --> 00:04:58.799
It was great.

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:03.839
They clearly didn't catch enough typos, as I found out later.

00:05:03.839 --> 00:05:10.399
And then it just kind of sat around there until eventually people started finding it.

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:13.640
So what did I learn from this experience?

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:19.640
Well, I mean, I would like to be able to say that, like, you know, the experience of being

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:24.980
a beginner and working through and learning it, I don't want to say I suffer from expert

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:33.019
bias in this, because I'm not really an expert, but I didn't get that part of it, you know.

00:05:33.019 --> 00:05:39.059
So if one is wondering, this is the thread where the Clojure name came from.

00:05:39.059 --> 00:05:45.480
So I had a bit of experience with Tidyverse, but I learned a lot through those books.

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:49.980
But I found most of the stuff in practice I ended up learning from all of it is, one,

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:54.700
if you put stuff on GitHub and make it public, some people might find it useful.

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:57.619
And that's really what happened here.

00:05:57.619 --> 00:06:01.140
Second, I make lots of typos.

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:06.019
So I spent a lot of time, kind of technical fixes to that, because I kind of didn't want

00:06:06.019 --> 00:06:09.380
to go back and proofread everything.

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:13.100
And I've been using this kind of as an opportunity to learn new things.

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:17.420
So when, you know, new markdown stuff comes up, I try it out.

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:23.579
If I want to learn some more JavaScript or some other sort of new technology, I test it out here.

00:06:23.579 --> 00:06:29.980
So first thing I do, like, I end up building up a lot of automation in terms of deployment

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:30.980
of this.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:34.299
You know, it uses bookdown to build it.

00:06:34.299 --> 00:06:38.779
Travis commits it and deploys it to GitHub Pages.

00:06:38.779 --> 00:06:43.380
But then I go through a lot of different things of check the spelling using our open size

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:49.779
spelling package, linter, styler, and then a lot of extra stuff, like I lint the markdown,

00:06:49.779 --> 00:06:53.940
I check the HTML, I check for all the broken links.

00:06:53.940 --> 00:06:56.019
This can be kind of quite useful.

00:06:56.019 --> 00:07:00.220
Here's one that came up yesterday or so.

00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:07.040
The HTML linter found that the ID of something generated by HTML widgets was a duplicate.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:10.739
So there would have been a double image in there that I would have never found.

00:07:10.739 --> 00:07:17.660
And I picked it up and, you know, removed the caching and fixed it after a bit of annoyance.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:21.420
But this is something that picked up.

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:24.540
So been building up that over time, same sort of thing.

00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:31.700
After it's built, check all the links, all 16,000 of them, to make sure that they're

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:32.820
still working.

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:38.839
This picks up things like, you know, spelling exercises wrong or whatnot.

00:07:38.839 --> 00:07:43.500
A second thing I like to do is trying to, like, reduce friction in getting user feedback.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:49.220
So, you know, it's been helpful, as I put it up, people found it, and I just kind of

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:51.579
responded as people brought up things.

00:07:51.579 --> 00:07:54.299
So this is one of my favorite ones.

00:07:54.299 --> 00:08:00.980
The question is, brainstorm as many ways as possible to select depth time, depth delay,

00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:02.579
R time, and R array from flight.

00:08:02.579 --> 00:08:06.579
So a bunch of different ways to do the select command.

00:08:06.579 --> 00:08:08.220
I was all clever.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:10.260
I mentioned the numbers.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:17.579
And then I say things like, this is bad, it's obfuscated, what do these columns mean?

00:08:17.579 --> 00:08:20.260
I don't know what column six is.

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:23.940
I just wrote the code and I've already forgotten.

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:32.580
Sure enough, I get an issue raised that I actually wrote in the wrong column after writing

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:33.580
that.

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:34.580
And it was not on purpose.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.979
I'm not that clever.

00:08:36.979 --> 00:08:39.179
But people catch that sort of stuff.

00:08:39.179 --> 00:08:41.900
And I think that's great.

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:45.099
And had some people contribute in various ways.

00:08:45.099 --> 00:08:50.700
I would love more contributions.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:54.059
But one thing with GitHub issues is just kind of how time-consuming they are.

00:08:54.059 --> 00:08:59.320
So these are a bunch from Greg Wilson, which are literally things like a, the, and a whole

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:01.840
bunch of just minor typos.

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:04.820
As I said, I make lots of typos.

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:08.900
Opening up a GitHub issue for all of those is kind of annoying.

00:09:08.900 --> 00:09:16.340
So I also tried putting on the service hypothesis, which allows annotation of websites.

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:20.440
So that's pretty nice in that it's a lot easier just to highlight something and leave a comment

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:26.299
and say this is misspelled, this is a typo, rather than opening up a GitHub issue.

00:09:26.299 --> 00:09:29.580
Some places you do want that extra friction for feedback.

00:09:29.580 --> 00:09:33.500
I think with these sort of things, you want less friction.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:37.500
But then I started thinking another way to go forward with it is simply to write something

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:44.140
where you can just highlight the text, and then it will open up a new GitHub issue that

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:51.340
has that highlighted text as the body of the issue, and, you know, links to the page where

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:52.340
that's occurring.

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:56.059
So in something like a document, that makes things a lot easier to submit, these sort

00:09:56.059 --> 00:10:03.280
of kind of minor, trivial, there's a typo here type issues.

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:08.479
Another thing I started looking at here was what could I learn from user behavior?

00:10:08.479 --> 00:10:15.159
So there's Google Analytics on it as of November when I started playing around with it.

00:10:15.159 --> 00:10:23.159
And so kind of thought I'd throw that information in and see what are the page views of people

00:10:23.159 --> 00:10:30.780
on these various chapters of R for Data Science solutions.

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:36.020
So the top are the highest chapters going from like the first couple intros, and you

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:42.539
see data visualization has lots of page views, then transformations have a little less, and

00:10:42.539 --> 00:10:49.419
it kind of decreases rapidly as one would expect in that sort of behavior.

00:10:49.419 --> 00:10:55.179
But can we maybe say something about which ones seem to be harder or which ones people

00:10:55.179 --> 00:10:57.260
are turning to?

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:01.659
And one problem with that is the number of exercises in R for Data Science vary dramatically

00:11:01.659 --> 00:11:03.059
with each chapter.

00:11:03.059 --> 00:11:04.059
Okay.

00:11:04.059 --> 00:11:08.380
So data visualization, transformation also have a lot of exercises.

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:12.219
Strings has a ton of exercises.

00:11:12.219 --> 00:11:18.780
But let's go ahead and put together a simple statistical model, a model unique users viewing

00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:25.380
the page as a function of chapter and exercises, and then look for pages that are not explained

00:11:25.460 --> 00:11:31.940
well by it as being potentially very hard or very easy, or ones that people want to

00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:33.859
view otherwise.

00:11:33.859 --> 00:11:40.500
And we see that like exploratory data analysis, the third major chapter seems to be receiving

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:43.619
fewer page users than expected.

00:11:43.619 --> 00:11:46.419
People seem to tail off at the end.

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:52.619
But iteration and the beginning of the modeling chapters seem to get lots of users, even given

00:11:52.619 --> 00:12:03.460
how far into the book they are and the number of exercises they have.

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:08.940
So with that, I kind of want to know, you know, what's next with this?

00:12:08.940 --> 00:12:16.820
And basically, I really only had one goal here, just saying that this solution exists.

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:18.539
They're up on GitHub.

00:12:18.539 --> 00:12:21.260
They're there for people to contribute.

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:24.940
I'm not trying to keep this my own.

00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:31.700
I'd love everyone to, if you see something wrong, if you see ways it can be improved,

00:12:31.700 --> 00:12:32.700
contribute at it.

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:35.419
I'd love to open this up as much as possible.

00:12:35.419 --> 00:12:37.140
Those are the links to it.

00:12:37.140 --> 00:12:40.140
And that's my information.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:43.140
Thank you.

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:46.140
Thank you.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:53.979
We have a few minutes for questions.

00:12:53.979 --> 00:12:54.979
We have a few mics.

00:12:54.979 --> 00:13:00.140
We have the throwable mics like we had in the opening keynote.

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:05.659
We've got one over here.

00:13:05.659 --> 00:13:06.659
Hello.

00:13:06.659 --> 00:13:07.659
Hey, Jeff.

00:13:07.659 --> 00:13:08.659
Hi.

00:13:08.659 --> 00:13:14.219
I really appreciated the infrastructure you put together around testing the HTML and stuff

00:13:14.219 --> 00:13:15.219
like that.

00:13:15.219 --> 00:13:17.659
Like, I'd really like to implement that with some things that I've done.

00:13:17.659 --> 00:13:23.659
Have you written anywhere about a way to do that or a guide or something?

00:13:23.659 --> 00:13:28.940
I have not written a guide to do that, and it's kind of a lot of this has just evolved

00:13:28.940 --> 00:13:33.380
as I've tried things out.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:36.380
You can check out the source code of it.

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:40.099
One thing I've tended to use, at least for the HTML and markdown, has been actually to

00:13:40.099 --> 00:13:45.820
turn to Node and JavaScript packages, just because there's so much web infrastructure

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:46.820
there.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:51.820
It seemed to be easier to implement.

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:53.780
But that's about all I have there.

00:13:53.780 --> 00:14:00.020
But I'll think about writing up more on that.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:05.580
So which book are you doing next?

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:17.419
I don't know.

00:14:17.419 --> 00:14:24.219
The one thing I didn't get to, which I would love to ask Hadley at some point, was what

00:14:24.219 --> 00:14:26.859
is the deal with the nursery rhymes?

00:14:26.859 --> 00:14:36.580
I know it started with Little Bunny Foo Foo, but then there's multiple exercises in R for

00:14:36.580 --> 00:14:41.619
Data Science about implementing nursery rhymes in other songs.

00:14:41.619 --> 00:14:45.260
In my memory, it was pages of these.

00:14:45.260 --> 00:14:48.820
In reality, there's only three questions.

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:53.460
But since I had time, I should have put it in there.

00:14:53.460 --> 00:15:00.500
But for what it's worth, the Baby Shark song seems to be one that would fall under that

00:15:00.500 --> 00:15:03.419
rubric very well.

00:15:03.419 --> 00:15:07.979
If they threw this back up, I have a very nice version that uses map in there.

00:15:07.979 --> 00:15:14.619
You can turn nested for loops into multiple intervals.

00:15:14.619 --> 00:15:25.539
So that might be the next song to become an R programming teaching tool.

